Tun unity oi the Dialogue has been the subiect of much discussion. No two editors are altogether agreed about its scheme or plan, and even its main motive has been called in question. We cannot pretend to determine now the extent to which the treatise embodies a conversation which may have actually occurred-how far it has a historical foundation, and how far it is the product ol the writer's imagination. There can be , no doubt, however, that it rests on a certain basis ol fact. The dramatis
